rs historical analysis of French Catholic intellectuals. This volume highlights the work of writers, thinkers and creative artists who have not always drawn the attention given to such luminaries as Maritain, Mounier, and Marcel.Organized around the typologies of renewal and engagement, editors Katherine Davies and Toby Garfitt provide a revisionist and interdisciplinary reading of the narrative of twentieth-century French Catholicism. Renewal and engagement are both manifestations of how the Catholic intellectual reflects and takes position on the relationship between the Church, personal faith and the world, and on the increasingly problematic relationship between intellectuals and the Magisterium. A majority of the writings are based on extensive research into published texts, with some occasional archival references, and they give critical insights into the tensions that characterized the theological and political concerns of their subjects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aCatholicszFrancexIntellectual lifey20th century. 4aCatholic Studies. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aCatholicism.  aFrench literature.  aJacques.  aMaritain.  aNouvelle théologie.1 aDavies, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunlop, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarfitt, Toby, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGarfitt, Toby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGifford, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Brenna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Mahony, Anthony, econtrib